<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-06-20T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-06-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="1236" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1236">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/4251.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Consul at Ciudad
                                    Juárez</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ciudad Juárez</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-06-20">
                                    <hi rend="italic">June 20, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Department’s June 19, 2 p.m. No Federal troops approaching Juárez.
                            Governor of Texas probably misinformed. Mexican consul <pb facs="1001" n="885" xml:id="pg_885"/> El Paso assures me no movement
                            contemplated at present for retaking Juárez. Personal observations
                            confirm this.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Edwards.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>